{"parse":{"title":"Borchert's Epochs","pageid":7215866,"revid":838860067,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Borchert's epochs</b> refer to five distinct periods in the history of <a href=\"/wiki/Urbanization_in_the_United_States\" title=\"Urbanization in the United States\">American urbanization</a> and are also known as Borchert's model of urban evolution. Each epoch is characterized by the impact of a particular transport technology on the creation and differential rates of growth of <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American</a> cities. This model was conceptualized by <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Minnesota\" title=\"University of Minnesota\">University of Minnesota</a> geographer John R. Borchert <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.borchert.com/john/\">(about)</a> in 1967. The five epochs identified by Borchert are:\n</p>\n<ul><li>Sail-Wagon Epoch (1790\u20131830), cities grow near ports and major waterways which are used for transportation;</li>\n<li>Iron Horse Epoch (1830\u201370), characterized by impact of steam engine technology, and development of steamboats and regional railroad networks;</li>\n<li>Steel Rail Epoch (1870\u20131920), dominated by the development of long haul railroads and a national railroad network;</li>\n<li>Auto-Air-Amenity Epoch (1920\u201370), with growth in the gasoline combustion engine;</li>\n<li>High-Technology Epoch (1970\u2013present), expansion in service and information sectors of the economy</li></ul>\n<p>Subsequent researchers (e.g., Phillips and Brunn) have proposed an extension of Borchert's model with new epochs to take into account late 20th-century developments in patterns of metropolitan growth and decline in the United States.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Borchert%27s_Epochs&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Borchert, John R. (July 1967). \"American Metropolitan Evolution\". <i>Geographical Review</i>. <b>57</b> (3): 301\u2013332. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.2307/212637\">10.2307/212637</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.jstor.org/stable/212637\">212637</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Geographical+Review&amp;rft.atitle=American+Metropolitan+Evolution&amp;rft.volume=57&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=301-332&amp;rft.date=1967-07&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F212637&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F212637&amp;rft.aulast=Borchert&amp;rft.aufirst=John+R.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABorchert%27s+Epochs\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Phillips, Phillip D.; Brunn, Stanley D. (July 1978). \"Slow Growth: A New Epoch of American Metropolitan Evolution\". <i>Geographical Review</i>. <b>68</b> (3): 274\u2013292. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.2307/215047\">10.2307/215047</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.jstor.org/stable/215047\">215047</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Geographical+Review&amp;rft.atitle=Slow+Growth%3A+A+New+Epoch+of+American+Metropolitan+Evolution&amp;rft.volume=68&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=274-292&amp;rft.date=1978-07&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F215047&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F215047&amp;rft.aulast=Phillips&amp;rft.aufirst=Phillip+D.&amp;rft.au=Brunn%2C+Stanley+D.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABorchert%27s+Epochs\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Kaplan; Wheeler; Holloway (2004). <i>Urban Geography</i>. John Wiley &amp; Sons, Inc. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-471-35998-X\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-471-35998-X\">0-471-35998-X</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Urban+Geography&amp;rft.pub=John+Wiley+%26+Sons%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.isbn=0-471-35998-X&amp;rft.au=Kaplan&amp;rft.au=Wheeler&amp;rft.au=Holloway&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABorchert%27s+Epochs\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">de Blij, H.J. &amp; Murphy, Alexander (2003). <i>Human Geography: Culture, Society, and Space</i>. John Wiley &amp; Sons, Inc. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-471-44107-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-471-44107-4\">0-471-44107-4</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Human+Geography%3A+Culture%2C+Society%2C+and+Space&amp;rft.pub=John+Wiley+%26+Sons%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=0-471-44107-4&amp;rft.au=de+Blij%2C+H.J.&amp;rft.au=Murphy%2C+Alexander&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABorchert%27s+Epochs\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">Ex